# Code Review — Mechanical Bug Checklist

Do not give a general impression. Run every check below against the code. Report each one as PASS, FAIL, or N/A. A FAIL means you explain exactly where the problem is and what the fix looks like.

---

## 1 — Async & Promises

- [ ] Every `async` function has error handling — no floating promises
- [ ] No `await` inside a loop without a deliberate reason (use `Promise.all` instead)
- [ ] No `async` function that returns a value where the return is never awaited by the caller
- [ ] Every `.then()` chain has a `.catch()` — or is inside a try/catch
- [ ] No `useEffect` with an async function directly — wrap it inside

```typescript
// FAIL pattern
useEffect(async () => { ... }, []);

// PASS pattern
useEffect(() => {
  const run = async () => { ... };
  run();
}, []);
```

---

## 2 — Database Queries

- [ ] No N+1 query pattern — fetching a list then querying inside a loop for each item
- [ ] No `SELECT *` in production queries — only fetch the columns you need
- [ ] No raw string interpolation in queries — parameterized queries only
- [ ] Large result sets are paginated — no unbounded queries on user-facing routes
- [ ] Queries on filtered or sorted columns have corresponding indexes
- [ ] Transactions used where multiple writes must succeed or fail together

---

## 3 — Security

- [ ] No hardcoded values that should be environment variables (API keys, URLs, credentials)
- [ ] No `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` without sanitization
- [ ] User input is never directly used in a file path, shell command, or eval
- [ ] No sensitive data (tokens, passwords, PII) written to logs or console
- [ ] Authorization check happens before the data fetch — not after

---

## 4 — State & Side Effects

- [ ] No state mutation — always use the setter function, never mutate directly
- [ ] No stale closure — variables inside useEffect are either in the dependency array or stable refs
- [ ] No derived state stored in useState when it could be computed from existing state
- [ ] No side effects triggered inside render — only inside useEffect or event handlers
- [ ] Cleanup runs on unmount — subscriptions, timers, event listeners, and fetch aborts

---

## 5 — TypeScript

- [ ] No `any` type without a comment explaining why it cannot be typed
- [ ] API response types are explicitly defined — not inferred as `any` from fetch
- [ ] All function parameters and return types are typed in shared/utility code
- [ ] No non-null assertion (`!`) on a value that could realistically be null
- [ ] Enums or const maps used for repeated string values — no magic strings

---

## 6 — Error Handling

- [ ] Every catch block does something — no empty `catch {}` that swallows errors silently
- [ ] Errors shown to the user are human-readable — no "Error: undefined" in the UI
- [ ] Network errors, 4xx, and 5xx are all handled distinctly where it matters
- [ ] Loading, error, and empty states all exist for every data-fetching component

---

## 7 — Performance Red Flags

- [ ] No expensive computation inside render without useMemo
- [ ] No function recreated on every render passed as a prop without useCallback
- [ ] No large imports loaded at the top level that could be lazy-loaded
- [ ] Images have explicit width and height — no layout shift
- [ ] No polling where a subscription or webhook would work

---

## 8 — Code Quality

- [ ] No function longer than 50 lines without a clear reason
- [ ] No deeply nested conditionals (3+ levels) — flatten with early returns
- [ ] No duplicated logic that should be a shared utility
- [ ] Variable and function names describe what the thing IS or DOES — no `data`, `temp`, `stuff`
- [ ] No dead code — commented-out blocks, unused variables, unreachable branches

---

## Review Output Format

After running all checks, output:

```
CODE REVIEW RESULT
──────────────────
FAILs found: [number]
Critical (must fix before merge): [list]
Minor (fix soon): [list]
Verdict: APPROVE / REQUEST CHANGES
```

If FAILs exist — show the exact line and the fix. Not a description. The actual code.
